For example, an astronomer might observe the motion of celestial bodies and then develop a theory to explain their movement. These observations are essential because they provide concrete evidence that can be tested and potentially refuted.

Theories, in contrast, are broader constructs that seek to explain why and how observations occur. A theory must be able to predict future observations and account for past ones. For instance, the theory of gravity explains why objects fall to the ground and how planets orbit the sun.
